            en: `Ancient Hindu texts describe Varanasi as Kashi, the city of light, believed to be founded by Lord Shiva himself. For more than 3,000 years, sages, saints, and seekers have walked its narrow lanes, believing that this city offers something rareâ€”liberation from the cycle of birth and death. Varanasi is not just a city on the map. It is a city in memory, in prayer, and in belief. People say that while kingdoms rose and fell across the world, Varanasi simply continued to existâ€”watching time pass from the banks of the Ganga. Varanasi has seen wars, invasions, and destruction. Temples were broken and rebuilt. Empires ruled and disappeared. Yet the city never stopped breathing. Every morning, the Ganga still welcomed thousands for prayer. Every evening, lamps still floated on her waters. Life and death continued side by side at the ghats, just as they had for centuries. Historically, Varanasi flourished as a major center of education, philosophy, music, and trade. Students came here to study philosophy, astronomy, Ayurveda, music, and Sanskrit. For thousands of years, sages, scholars, pilgrims, and travelers have walked its winding lanes, all drawn by the same hopeâ€”to find truth, peace, and freedom from the cycle of birth and death. It attracted scholars from across India and beyond. The city also played a key role in the rise of Buddhism. Buddhism also touched the city's soulâ€”nearby Sarnath is where Gautama Buddha delivered his first sermon, adding another spiritual layer to the region.

The city witnessed invasions, political changes, and periods of destruction during medieval times. Temples were broken, rebuilt, and reborn. Yet, Varanasi never lost its essence. The Ganga continued to flow, and rituals continued without pauseâ€”quiet proof of the city's unbreakable spirit.`,
